About the Dataset¶

This Project is utilizing the Sleep Health and Lifestyle Dataset in Kaggle, A secondary Data. This is basically measuring the impart of someone's lifestyle on their health.

The Dataset contains 14 columns in total (That is, 13 features and 1 classification columns with 3 labels/category/mulitclass - None, Sleep Aspnea and Insomnia). The dataset contains 374 rows in total excluding the data header row

The 13 features includes; Person Identifier (ID), Gender (Male/Female), Age (In years), Occupation(Profession of the Person), Sleep duration (In hours per day), Quality of Sleep (On a scale rating 1-10 with 1- no significance, 5-medium significance and 9/10-high significance...It is a subjectice rating based on feelings and opinions), Physical Activity Level (In minutes per day, Stress Level (On a scale rating of 1-10, measure how stress level experienced by the Individual, it is also subjective rating), Systolic Blood Pressure in mmHg, Diastolic Blood Pressure in mmHg, Heart rate in bpm (Beat per minutes), Daily Steps (In count), The Classification Column is the SLEEP DISORDER COLUMN with 3 labels - None, Sleep Apnea and Insomnia

The Aim of this Project¶

This study aimed at utilising logistics Regression and Randomforest to model the best predictors for determining what features affect the sleep health of some certain Professions based on their Lifestyle and classifying the Sleep Disorder class.

Intrepretability Using Statistical Techniques like Variance Inflation Factor and Correlation HeatMap¶

Detecting multicollinearity between predictors One method to detect multicollinearity is to calculate the variance inflation factor (VIF) for each independent variable, and a VIF value greater than 1.5 indicates multicollinearity.

** Multicollinearity occurs when there are two or more independent variables in a multiple regression model, which have a high correlation among themselves. When some features are highly correlated, we might have difficulty in distinguishing between their individual effects on the dependent variable.

In [25]:
from statsmodels.stats.outliers_influence import variance_inflation_factor

# the independent variables set
Independent_Sleep_Variables = Sleep_Lifestyle_dt_2[['Gender', 'Age', 'Occupation', 'Sleep Duration', 'Quality of Sleep', 'Physical Activity Level', 'Stress Level', 'BMI Category', 'Systolic Blood Pressure', 'Diastolic Blood Pressure', 'Heart Rate', 'Daily Steps']]

# VIF dataframe
vif = pd.DataFrame()
vif["feature"] = Independent_Sleep_Variables.columns

# calculating VIF for each feature
vif["VIF"] = [variance_inflation_factor(Independent_Sleep_Variables.values, i)
                          for i in range(len(Independent_Sleep_Variables.columns))]

print(vif)

Building and Evaluating the Models¶

** Before buidling the logistics Regression Model,

  1. The class distribution is checked for to know if the data class distribution is balanced or imbalanced. If the class distribution is IMBALANCED, SMOTE will be applied after the train-test split, this is to avoid DATA LEAKAGE which can lead to Over-optimistic results and unrealistic performance evaluation.
  2. It is also recommended that the SMOTE is applied to the Training sets alone which balances the class distribution for train data without affecting the Test sets. After which, it is scaled/normalized differently - Scale/Normalize the Train set and test set differently.
  3. Evaluate and Build the Model.

This is approach that would be used in this project.... After considering the algorithm requirements, Logistics regression used in this project was standardized instead of normalized, this is because using StandardScaler to scale the features works better for logistics model works better than normalized data except if you want your data to be scaled between a particular/fixed range.

Splitting the Dataset into Training and Test sets¶

The stratify=y is used to ensure that the class distrubution in the training and test sets is similar to the class distribution in the original dataset. It ensures that the proportion of each class label is preserved in both training and test sets.This is particularly important for imbalanced datasets where some classes are underrepresented...

In [30]:
#Split the data into train-test sample before smote on the Train data....and then standardize both the train and test data.

from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split

# Split the data into training and test sets
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.3, random_state=123, stratify=y)

Applying SMOTE on the Training Set and Leaving the Test sets out to avoid Data Leakage¶

Data Leakage is the scenario where the Machine Learning Model is already aware of some part of test data after training.This causes the problem of overfitting. DATA LEAKAGE which can lead to Over-optimistic results and unrealistic performance evaluation. This is why the Test Set was left out in the Smote process

In [31]:
from imblearn.over_sampling import SMOTE

# Applying SMOTE to the training data
sm = SMOTE(random_state=12345)
X_train_resampled, y_train_resampled = sm.fit_resample(X_train, y_train)

Building the Logistics Regression Model with the Scaled Dataset¶

After considering the algorithm requirements, Logistics regression used in this project was standardized instead of normalized, this is because using StandardScaler to scale the features works better for logistics model works better than normalized data except if you want your data to be scaled between a particular/fixed range

In [36]:
from sklearn.linear_model import LogisticRegression
from sklearn.metrics import classification_report, roc_curve, roc_auc_score

# Logistic Regression model training using scaled train and test set
model = LogisticRegression()
model.fit(X_train_resampled_scaled, y_train_resampled)


# Predicting the probabilities on the test set to allow for computing the ROC-AUC curves
y_pred_proba = model.predict_proba(X_test_scaled)

# One-vs-Rest(ovr) ROC curves approach is used, which means treating each class as the positive class and the rest as negative.
fpr = {}
tpr = {}
roc_auc = {}

# Computing ROC curve and ROC area for each class
for i in range(3):
    fpr[i], tpr[i], _ = roc_curve(y_test, y_pred_proba[:, i], pos_label=i)
    roc_auc[i] = roc_auc_score(y_test == i, y_pred_proba[:, i])

# Plotting ROC curve for each class
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 8))
for i in range(3):
    plt.plot(fpr[i], tpr[i], lw=2, label=f'ROC curve of class {i} (area = {roc_auc[i]:0.2f})')

plt.plot([0, 1], [0, 1], 'k--', lw=2)
plt.xlim([0.0, 1.0])
plt.ylim([0.0, 1.05])
plt.xlabel('False Positive Rate')
plt.ylabel('True Positive Rate')
plt.title('Receiver Operating Characteristic (ROC) Curve')
plt.legend(loc="lower right")
plt.show()

# Predicting on the test set
y_pred = model.predict(X_test_scaled)

# Computimg the Classification Report on the Test data , Precision, Recall and F1-score for the multiclass
print(classification_report(y_test, y_pred))

# Calculate overall AUC
overall_auc = roc_auc_score(y_test, y_pred_proba, multi_class="ovr")
print(f'Overall AUC: {overall_auc:.2f}')


# Confusion Matrix for the logistics model built
conf_matrix = confusion_matrix(y_test, y_pred)

# Plotting Confusion Matrix
plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))
sns.heatmap(conf_matrix, annot=True, cmap="plasma", fmt="d")
plt.xlabel('Predicted label')
plt.ylabel('True label')
plt.title('Confusion Matrix')
plt.show()

Building the Logistics Regression model with Lasso(L1 Regularization)¶

This is used to perform feature selection by shriking the less importance feature co-efficients to zero

In [37]:
from sklearn.linear_model import LogisticRegression

# Training a Logistic Regression model with L1 regularization
log_reg = LogisticRegression(penalty='l1', solver='saga', random_state=42)
log_reg.fit(X_train_resampled_scaled, y_train_resampled)

# Get the coefficients
coef = log_reg.coef_[0]

# Printing the feature importance
print("Feature importance (Logistic Regression with L1):")
for i, feature in enumerate(X.columns):
    print(f"{feature}: {coef[i]}")

# Plotting the  feature importance
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 8))
plt.bar(X.columns, coef)
plt.xticks(rotation=90)
plt.title("Feature importance (Logistic Regression with L1)")
plt.show()

Permutation Importance on Logistic Regression Model¶

**This can be used with any model to measure the effect of shuffling each feature on the model performance

** Permutation importance is a model-agnostic technique that helps determine the importance of features by measuring the increase in the model’s prediction error when the values of a single feature are randomly shuffled.

*** Positive Importance Scores: Feature is important for the model.

*** Near-Zero Scores: Feature is likely not contributing much to the model.

*** Negative Scores: Typically indicate noise or that the feature's shuffling accidentally improved the model due to noise in the dataset.

In [38]:
from sklearn.inspection import permutation_importance

# Training the model (Using Logistics Regression Classifier)
model = LogisticRegression()
model.fit(X_train_resampled_scaled, y_train_resampled)


# Computing the permutation importance
result = permutation_importance(model, X_test_scaled, y_test, n_repeats=10, random_state=42)

# Printing the feature importance
print("Permutation feature importance:")
for i in result.importances_mean.argsort()[::-1]:
    if result.importances_mean[i] - 2 * result.importances_std[i] > 0:
        print(f"{X.columns[i]}: {result.importances_mean[i]:.3f} +/- {result.importances_std[i]:.3f}")

# Plotting the feature importance
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 8))
plt.boxplot(result.importances.T, vert=False, labels=X.columns)
plt.title("Permutation feature importance")
plt.show()

Building a RandomForest Classifier¶

** Random Forest:is a Tree-based method which is generally robust to feature scaling, but sometimes it can benefit from scaling if there are significant disparities in feature ranges. So therefore, the scaled features would not be used but the actual smote training set and actual test set. However, for comparism the scaled and unscaled dataset would be used to check/prove the effect of feature scaling/normalizing on Tree based Models

Let's dive in

Building the RF Classifier using the scaled Train and Test data features¶
In [39]:
# Train the model using the scaled training set and test set...
### The results shows the same as with the unscaled training set and test set

from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestClassifier
from sklearn.metrics import classification_report, roc_curve, roc_auc_score

model = RandomForestClassifier(random_state=42)
model.fit(X_train_resampled_scaled, y_train_resampled)

# Predicting the probabilities on the test set
y_pred_proba = model.predict_proba(X_test_scaled)

# One-vs-Rest(ovr) ROC curves approach is used, which means treating each class as the positive class and the rest as negative.
fpr = {}
tpr = {}
roc_auc = {}

# Computing ROC curve and ROC area for each class
for i in range(3):
    fpr[i], tpr[i], _ = roc_curve(y_test, y_pred_proba[:, i], pos_label=i)
    roc_auc[i] = roc_auc_score(y_test == i, y_pred_proba[:, i])

# Plotting ROC curve for each class
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 8))
for i in range(3):
    plt.plot(fpr[i], tpr[i], lw=2, label=f'ROC curve of class {i} (area = {roc_auc[i]:0.2f})')

plt.plot([0, 1], [0, 1], 'k--', lw=2)
plt.xlim([0.0, 1.0])
plt.ylim([0.0, 1.05])
plt.xlabel('False Positive Rate')
plt.ylabel('True Positive Rate')
plt.title('Receiver Operating Characteristic (ROC) Curve')
plt.legend(loc="lower right")
plt.show()

# Printing the classification report
y_pred = model.predict(X_test_scaled)
print(classification_report(y_test, y_pred))

# Calculating the overall AUC
overall_auc = roc_auc_score(y_test, y_pred_proba, multi_class="ovr")
print(f'Overall AUC: {overall_auc:.2f}')


# Confusion Matrix for the Random Forest Classifier built
conf_matrix = confusion_matrix(y_test, y_pred)

# Plotting Confusion Matrix
plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))
sns.heatmap(conf_matrix, annot=True, cmap="PuOr", fmt="d")
plt.xlabel('Predicted label')
plt.ylabel('True label')
plt.title('Confusion Matrix')
plt.show()

# Get feature importances that contributes to the prediction of the model (Unscaled Dataset)
importances = model.feature_importances_
indices = np.argsort(importances)[::-1]

# Printing the feature ranking
print("Feature ranking:")

for f in range(X_train_resampled.shape[1]):
    print(f"{f + 1}. feature {indices[f]} ({importances[indices[f]]})")

Feature Importance Intrepretation from RF Classifier Feature Importance score and Permutation Importance Feature Score for logistics model and RandomForest Classifier¶

  1. The results of the feature importance score in RF classifier feature importance scores shows that the Systolic BP, Diastolic BP, Body Mass Index (BMI Category), Occupation, Physical Activity, Age, Sleep duration and Daily Step has significant effct on the target variable (which is, Sleep Disorder).

  2. Looking at the Permutation Feature scores diagram for RF model, shows Systolic BP, Occupation, Physical Activity Level, Diastolic BP, BMI Category affects the target variable (which is, Sleep Disorder).

  3. Logistic Regression built with Lasso Regularization shows that Quality of Sleep, Stress level and Gender shows a positive relationship with the target variable (which is, Sleep Disorder)

  4. Permutation Feature Importance Score on Logistics Regression, shows that Quality of Sleep> Diastolic BP> Sleep Duration> Age> Systolic BP> Daily Steps> Gender> Heart Rate> Stress Level> Physical Activity Level has impart on the target in that order.

From Research online from Sleep and Hypertension National Issue of Healths (NIH) article, it shows that Both sleep deprivation and insomnia have been linked to increases in incidence and prevalence of hypertension. (https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC2913764/)

It's also possible that HBP may make sleep more difficult. HBP occurs when the force of blood pumping through your veins is high. This puts stress on your blood vessels and can cause symptoms such as headaches, chest pain, and difficulty breathing. All these symptoms can make sleep difficult. Meanwhile, Sleep apnea is defined as a breathing disorder that affects sleep. (https://www.healthline.com/health/high-blood-pressure/can-high-blood-pressure-cause-insomnia)

In this Project, a multiclass a logistics regression (LR) model and Random Forest (RF) Model was built. LR has an accuracy of 87% and RF has an accuracy of 83% on the test data while both has an overall AUC of 91% indicates that the models has a high ability to distinguish between classes.
